graphs.title: Compressive stress–strain curves of Al0.5CoCrCuFeNi at various temperatures — high strain rate
graphs.description: Panel (a): High strain rate (10 s^-1) compression curves for Al0.5CoCrCuFeNi at multiple temperatures.
graphs.about_graph: Multiple engineering stress–engineering strain curves measured in compression at a strain rate of 10 s^-1; each curve corresponds to a different test temperature.

curves.about_curve: Represents material strength and work hardening at the lowest temperature in this panel.
curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Higher flow stress and lower thermal softening than higher-temperature curves.
curves.what_is_common_between_this_curve_and_ot: Same alloy, same loading mode (compression), same engineering axes and strain rate (10 s^-1).

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.030–0.076.

curves.about_curve: Shows moderate thermal softening relative to 300 °C.
curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Lower flow stress than 300 °C; higher than ≥700 °C curves.
curves.what_is_common_between_this_curve_and_ot: Same alloy, compression, engineering stress–strain, 10 s^-1.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.141–0.164.

curves.what_is_common_between_this_curve_and_ot: Same alloy and test conditions aside from temperature.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.146–0.164.

curves.about_curve: Near the upper useful temperature range reported for this alloy family.
curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Lower strength and greater ductility relative to ≤700 °C curves.
curves.what_is_common_between_this_curve_and_ot: Same alloy, compression, engineering axes, 10 s^-1.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.064–0.077.

curves.about_curve: Thermal softening continues; substantially reduced flow stress.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.038–0.077.

curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Lower strength than ≤900 °C; approaching very low flow stress.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.033–0.076.

curves.about_curve: Very low flow stress; extensive softening.
curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Among the lowest strengths of the set.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.042–0.077.

curves.about_curve: Lowest strength in this panel due to maximum thermal softening.
curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Minimum flow stress among all temperatures shown.
curves.what_is_common_between_this_curve_and_ot: Same alloy, compression, engineering axes, 10 s^-1.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.022–0.075.

Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.143–0.190.
Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.040–0.059.

curves.about_curve: Low flow stress and limited hardening.

curves.what_is_different_between_this_curve_and: Among the lowest strengths in the set.

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.022–0.078.

curves.about_curve: Lowest strength among temperatures shown in this panel.

curves.what_is_common_between_this_curve_and_ot: Same alloy, compression, engineering axes, 10^-3 s^-1.

graphs.title: Engineering stress–strain curve of Al0.5CoCrCuFeNi in tension at room temperature (10^-3 s^-1)
graphs.description: Uniaxial tensile test of Al0.5CoCrCuFeNi at room temperature and a strain rate of 10^-3 s^-1.
graphs.about_graph: Single engineering stress–engineering strain tensile curve; room temperature; quasi-static strain rate.

curves.curve_description: Al0.5CoCrCuFeNi tensile response at room temperature.
curves.about_curve: Shows high yield strength (~1.28 GPa) and UTS (~1.34 GPa) with finite ductility (per figure caption context).

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.007–0.012.

graphs.title: Engineering stress–strain curve of BCC-HEA (Al7.5Cr22.5Fe35Mn20Ni15) in compression at room temperature (10^-3 s^-1)
graphs.description: Uniaxial compression test of the BCC-HEA at room temperature and a strain rate of 10^-3 s^-1.
graphs.about_graph: Single engineering stress–engineering strain compression curve for the BCC-HEA composition.

curves.curve_description: BCC-HEA compression response at room temperature.
curves.about_curve: Shows high yield strength (~1.25 GPa) with substantial strain hardening to ~2.58 GPa (per figure caption context).

Kocks\u2013Mecking_hardening_parameters.comment: Parameters obtained by linear regression on θ vs σ in the strain window 0.021–0.079.
